🚀 Manual Setup Application
(Code → Build → Deploy)
By Ritik 
________________________________________
🎯 Purpose of the Project
The purpose of this project is to understand how an application is built and deployed manually, step by step.
In this project, we learn:
•	How code is written and managed 
•	How code is converted into an executable format (JAR) 
•	How an application is containerized using Docker 
•	How it is deployed on a server 
👉 This understanding is essential because modern DevOps automation (CI/CD) is built on top of this manual process.
________________________________________
❓ Why This Project is Important
In real-world environments:
•	Applications are not deployed manually 
•	Automation pipelines are used 
But to understand automation properly:
👉 You must first understand the manual workflow
This project helps you:
•	Understand real-world deployment flow 
•	Debug issues when systems fail 
•	Build a strong foundation for DevOps and Cloud 
________________________________________
🏗️ What We Are Building
We are taking a simple Java web application and:
1.	Building it 
2.	Packaging it into a JAR file 
3.	Converting it into a Docker image 
4.	Deploying it on a cloud server 
________________________________________
🔄 Overall Workflow
Developer → Code
⬇
Build Server → Build Application
⬇
Docker → Create Image
⬇
ECR → Store Image
⬇
Deploy Server → Run Application
⬇
User → Access via Browser
________________________________________
🧑‍💻 Step 1: Development Phase
✔️ What are we doing?
The developer writes and manages the application code.
✔️ Why are we doing this?
To create the base application logic.
✔️ How does it work?
•	Code is written locally 
•	Stored and managed using version control 
🎯 Output:
•	Source code is ready 
________________________________________
🛠️ Step 2: Build Phase
✔️ What are we doing?
We convert the source code into an executable format.
✔️ Why are we doing this?
Raw code cannot run directly
👉 It must be compiled into a runnable format (JAR)
✔️ How does it work?
•	Code is compiled 
•	Dependencies are added 
🎯 Output:
•	JAR file is generated (ready to run) 
________________________________________
▶️ Step 3: Application Testing
✔️ What are we doing?
We run the application locally to test it.
✔️ Why are we doing this?
To ensure the application works correctly before deployment
✔️ How does it work?
•	Application is started 
•	Tested through a browser 
🎯 Output:
•	Application runs successfully 
________________________________________
🐳 Step 4: Containerization (Docker)
✔️ What are we doing?
We package the application into a Docker container.
✔️ Why are we doing this?
•	To make the application portable 
•	To ensure it runs the same in all environments 
✔️ How does it work?
•	A Docker image is created 
•	A container is started from the image 
🎯 Output:
•	Application runs inside a container 
________________________________________
📦 Step 5: Image Storage (ECR)
✔️ What are we doing?
We store the Docker image in a cloud registry.
✔️ Why are we doing this?
•	To share the image with other servers 
•	To maintain centralized storage 
✔️ How does it work?
•	The image is pushed to a registry 
🎯 Output:
•	Image is available in the cloud 
________________________________________
🚀 Step 6: Deployment Phase
✔️ What are we doing?
We deploy the application on a server.
✔️ Why are we doing this?
To make the application accessible to users
✔️ How does it work?
•	Server pulls the image 
•	Runs the container 
🎯 Output:
•	Application is live and accessible 
________________________________________
🌐 Final Output
Users can access the application through a browser using the server’s public IP.
________________________________________
⚠️ Key Concepts Learned
•	Difference between build and run 
•	Importance of JAR files 
•	Role of Docker containers 
•	Concept of port mapping 
•	End-to-end cloud deployment flow 
________________________________________
💡 Final Understanding
After completing this project, you will clearly understand:
•	The journey from code to production 
•	Each manual step involved in deployment 
•	The foundation of DevOps pipelines 
________________________________________
🚀 Next Step
You are now ready to:
•	Learn CI/CD pipelines 
•	Use automation tools like Jenkins or GitHub Actions 
•	Work on real production deployments 
